title: loosen assert.fail typings and change assert.throws and .doesNotThrow to overload syntax
body:
`assert.fail` can be called with optional `message` and `operator` parameters. The API docs as far back as Node 4 (https://nodejs.org/docs/v4.8.3/api/assert.html#assert_assert_fail_actual_expected_message_operator) show `message` being passed as undefined in an example, and as of Node 8 they have also supported calling with a single argument meaning `message`. (https://nodejs.org/docs/v8.0.0/api/assert.html#assert_assert_fail_message)

See also Node's own code that uses `assert.fail` with no operator passed. (https://github.com/nodejs/node/blob/v4.x/lib/assert.js#L345)

This PR loosens the assert.fail typings for Node v4, v6, and v7 accordingly, and adds the assert.fail(message) overload to Node v8.

import MediaQuery from 'react-responsive';

);

title: [seamless-immutable] replace `any` with meaningful types, enforce string property typing, fix bugs
body:
There're a few problems with current version of type definitions that this pull request addresses:

1. Type checking is not performed in many places using `any` rather than a generic type.
2. No property name type-check. For example, we ideally shouldn't allow to do this:
`state.set('foo', 1) // state type doesn't have the property foo`
3. Types are sometimes wrong. For example, methods shouldn't return solely the mixin part
 `ImmutableObject<any>`, but rather the type plus the mixin part `T & ImmutableObjectMixin<T>`.
